l Innovation in Higher Education offers a different vision by identifying the conditions that enable college and university administrators, faculty, and staff to promote an innovative institutional culture. Mindful innovation is defined through six central tenets: societal impact; the necessity of failure; creativity through diversity; respect for autonomy and expertise; thoughtful consideration for the dimensions of time, efficiency, and trust; and the incentivization of intrinsic motivation and progress over scare tactics and disruption. Michael Lanford and William G. Tierney offer a clearheaded analysis of the challenges and opportunities in creating a culture of mindful innovation and argue that the institutions that do so will be poised to lead entrepreneurial endeavors, scientific progress, and greater social equity in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEducationxAims and objectives. 0aEducational change. 0aEducational psychology. 0aMindfulness (Psychology). 0aSchool environment. 4aBusiness and Economics : Organization Theory. 4aEducation : Education Policy and Leadership. 4aEducation : Educational Research. 4aEducation : Higher Education. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aTierney, William G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848764940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438487649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438487649/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles